                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 LCC/15: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-02-14T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >February 14, 1944—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1120. We are in complete accord with the suggested British line of approach to
                    the Russians set forth in paragraph 7 of your 1209, February 12, 5 p.m.</p>
                <p>We do not agree with your interpretation of paragraph 3 in numbered paragraph 2
                    of Sargent’s communication. It appears to <pb facs="1475" n="1461"
                        xml:id="pg_1461"/> us that Sir Orme is not proposing that the LPC assume the
                    weekly directive function but is merely confirming the present practice whereby
                    the weekly directive is drafted by the PWE and OWI in London and then submitted
                    for final decision to the Overseas Planning Board in Washington and presumably
                    to the appropriate branches of the British Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
